<font color="#FF0000">TO BETTY</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 27 19:37:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Betty,<br><br>
You do have a voice! What I am finding out is that we don't have to write our service *out of our resumes* any longer.<br><br>
Use your voice, because that is the only way you will be heard. And never grow impatient.<br><br>
Edward Ramon talks about how he has found that &quot;acceptance heals emotional wounds&quot;. I am not able to gauge the extent of any one's emotional wounds. Wounds occur in battle. Others may have occurred when we returned home - such as the discovery that our parents failed to save letters we sent them, as you mention.<br><br>
You were not wrong to desire acceptance then or now. Acceptance is easier for those who humped the boonies or who flew Combat Assaults. Sometimes a person has to *fight* for acceptance. This is something that is not so unusual in our country. Women, above all, understand this. I know you do.<br><br>
So tell us, and don't sell yourself short by &quot;comparing&quot; or getting into &quot;contests&quot;.<br><br>
The bomb crater I am talking about was not a large &quot;swimming pool&quot; variety that we often encountered. I don't know much about ordnance as far as what size craters individual bombs make. <br><br>
The whole episode has been written and hopefully (a dream of mine, actually) will appear with a copyright slapped on it. There is nothing that would please me more than to have Cook Barela shell out $17.95 to read about it!<br><br>
Peace to you Betty. Keep on keepin' on.
<p><code>-- wingman%greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


